transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Hello, and thank you for having me. I appreciate the opportunity to share my experiences. I'm ready when you are!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Sure! As I mentioned, my name is Leah. I'm 39 years old and I run a small business here in Chicago. I have a master's degree, which I think has really helped me in managing my business effectively. I'm married and in a committed relationship, and we focus a lot on maintaining a healthy lifestyle together. 

I make it a point to exercise regularly, and I try to eat well, especially since I have a few health conditions like prediabetes and hypertension. It's been a journey managing those, but I’ve learned to keep them under control. I also have asthma, but it's well-managed with my medication. 

Overall, I feel fortunate to have private health insurance, which has made it easier for me to access the care I need. I'm not planning on having any more children, given my previous experiences with cesarean deliveries. I’m currently using hormonal contraception to help with that. 

How about you? What would you like to know next?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Of course. I learned I was pregnant for the first time about 10 years ago. It was a bit of a surprise, but I was excited nonetheless. My first pregnancy went fairly well initially, but I ended up needing a cesarean delivery because of some complications during labor. 

After that, I had my second child a few years later, and the same thing happened—another cesarean delivery. While both pregnancies had their challenges, I was grateful to have a supportive partner and a good healthcare team guiding me through the process. 

I think the most challenging part for me was adjusting to the recovery after the surgeries, but I was determined to be active and healthy for my children. 

Do you want to know more about any specific aspects of my pregnancies or the care I received during that time?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I first sought prenatal care shortly after I learned I was pregnant with my first child, around the 8-week mark. I remember feeling a mix of excitement and anxiety as I scheduled my first appointment. The experience itself was relatively positive. My healthcare provider was very supportive and took the time to answer all my questions, which helped ease my worries.

During the first few visits, I appreciated the thoroughness of the exams and the information I received about what to expect throughout the pregnancy. They monitored my health closely, especially since I have prediabetes and hypertension, and I felt reassured knowing they were keeping an eye on those conditions. 

However, I did feel that sometimes the appointments felt rushed, and I wished there had been more time for discussions about my specific concerns, especially regarding my previous health issues. I found myself having to advocate for more information about how my pre-existing conditions could affect my pregnancies.

After my first cesarean delivery, I was aware that I might face similar challenges with my second pregnancy, so I sought care early again. The experience was much the same, but I felt more prepared with the knowledge I had gained from my first pregnancy. 

Is there anything specific about the prenatal care process that you would like me to elaborate on?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
My prenatal care was provided by a team at a local obstetrics clinic. I primarily saw an obstetrician who specialized in high-risk pregnancies, which was important to me given my history of prediabetes and hypertension. I also had regular check-ins with a nurse practitioner who was very attentive and always took the time to listen to my concerns.

I would say my relationship with my healthcare provider was generally positive. They were knowledgeable and supportive, which made a big difference, especially during my first pregnancy when I had so many questions and uncertainties. I felt comfortable discussing my health history with them, and they made an effort to explain how my pre-existing conditions could affect my pregnancy and delivery options.

However, there were times when I felt like the appointments were a bit rushed, and I wished for more time to discuss my specific concerns. It sometimes felt like I had to advocate for myself to ensure all my questions were thoroughly answered. Overall, though, I appreciated the expertise they brought to my care, and I felt that they were genuinely invested in my health and the health of my baby.

Would you like to know more about any specific interactions I had with my healthcare provider or how they managed my health conditions during my pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Certainly! During my pregnancies, I had prenatal appointments every four weeks during the first trimester, then every two weeks as I moved into the third trimester, and finally, weekly as I approached my due date. It felt like I was in the clinic quite a bit, but I appreciated the regular check-ins, especially given my pre-existing conditions.

A typical visit usually started with checking in with the nurse, who would take my blood pressure and weight, and ask about any changes in my health or concerns I might have had since my last visit. This was important since I had to keep an eye on my hypertension and blood sugar levels.

After that, I would meet with my obstetrician. They would go over any lab results, listen to the baby’s heartbeat, and conduct a physical exam to check on the growth and positioning of the baby. I always found it reassuring to hear the heartbeat; it made everything feel more real.

During the visits, I would ask questions about my health, the baby’s development, and what to expect in the coming weeks. There were times when I felt like I wanted more information on how my health conditions could affect my pregnancy, and I would sometimes have to remind the doctor to address those concerns more thoroughly.

Towards the end of my pregnancy, the discussions shifted to delivery options, recovery, and postnatal care, which was a bit daunting. It was a lot to take in, but I felt supported overall.

Do you have any specific questions about the appointments or how they addressed my health needs?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Yes, I did experience some health concerns during my pregnancies. With both pregnancies, my prediabetes and hypertension were closely monitored. I had to be vigilant about my diet and exercise to keep my blood sugar levels stable, and I was on medication to manage my blood pressure.

During my first pregnancy, I experienced some additional complications that led to the decision for a cesarean delivery. I had elevated blood pressure readings that required extra monitoring, and there were times when I felt a bit overwhelmed trying to balance my health with the pregnancy. Thankfully, my healthcare team was very proactive in managing those issues, which helped me feel more secure.

My second pregnancy was a bit smoother overall, but I still faced the same challenges with prediabetes and hypertension. There were days when I felt anxious about how those conditions might affect the pregnancy and the delivery, but my provider reassured me and helped me set realistic goals for managing my health.

I think one of the biggest challenges I faced was the emotional toll of worrying about these health conditions and their impact on my baby. It was comforting to know I had a supportive partner and a dedicated healthcare team, but I still found myself feeling anxious at times.

Is there anything specific you'd like to know about how I managed these health concerns during my pregnancies or how they were addressed by my healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I'm currently taking a few medications to help manage my health conditions. For my hypertension, I'm on a medication called lisinopril, which has been effective in keeping my blood pressure within a normal range. For my prediabetes, I've made significant lifestyle changes, including diet and exercise, but I also take metformin to help with blood sugar control. 

As for asthma, I use an inhaler as needed and a daily inhalation medication to keep my symptoms well-managed. Additionally, I take a prenatal vitamin supplement, which my doctor recommended even though I'm not currently pregnant, to support my overall health and nutrition. 

I try to stay on top of my medications and have regular check-ins with my healthcare provider to ensure everything is working as it should. It can feel overwhelming at times, but I understand the importance of managing these conditions, especially as a busy small business owner.

Do you have any questions about how I manage these medications or how they fit into my overall health plan?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I really focused on maintaining a balanced diet to support my health and the baby's development. Given my prediabetes, I was particularly mindful of my carbohydrate intake and tried to choose whole grains, lean proteins, and plenty of fruits and vegetables. I worked with my healthcare provider to develop a meal plan that would help keep my blood sugar levels stable while still providing the necessary nutrients for pregnancy.

I also made sure to stay hydrated and limited my intake of sugary snacks and beverages. Instead, I opted for healthy snacks like nuts, yogurt, and fresh fruit, which helped me manage my cravings in a healthier way. I found that meal prepping worked well for me, as it allowed me to have healthy options readily available, especially during busy days running my business.

In addition, I paid attention to my iron intake because of my anemia. I included foods rich in iron, like spinach, lentils, and lean meats, and I paired them with vitamin C-rich foods to enhance absorption. My healthcare provider also recommended an iron supplement to help me maintain healthy levels, which I incorporated into my routine.

Overall, I felt that my dietary choices during pregnancy were crucial not only for managing my health conditions but also for ensuring a healthy environment for my baby. I found it empowering to take charge of my nutrition, even amidst the challenges of pregnancy.

Is there anything more specific you’d like to know about my diet or how it impacted my pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, my emotional state was quite a rollercoaster. Initially, I felt a lot of excitement and joy at the thought of becoming a mother, but there were also moments of anxiety and stress, especially given my health conditions. 

With my first pregnancy, I experienced a fair amount of worry about how my prediabetes and hypertension would affect both me and the baby. The added pressure of managing those conditions while preparing for childbirth was overwhelming at times. I often found myself second-guessing my choices and feeling concerned about my health and the potential complications that could arise. Thankfully, my partner was very supportive, which helped ease some of my worries.

As I moved into my second pregnancy, I felt more prepared because I had gone through the experience once before. However, the anxiety never fully went away. I think the emotional toll of worrying about my health conditions and their impact was present throughout both pregnancies. I tried to stay positive and focused on the joy of welcoming a new life, but moments of doubt and fear would creep in.

I also found that talking about my feelings with my healthcare provider and my partner was helpful. They provided reassurance and support, which made a big difference in managing my emotions. 

Overall, I would say it was a mix of excitement, joy, and anxiety. Understanding that these feelings were normal helped me navigate through the emotional ups and downs of pregnancy.

Is there anything specific you'd like to know about how I coped with my emotions during pregnancy or how I managed stress?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I’m fortunate to have a really strong support network during my pregnancies. My partner has been my biggest source of support. He was there for me through both pregnancies, helping me navigate the physical and emotional challenges. We made a point to communicate openly about our feelings and concerns, which really helped us feel connected and prepared for parenthood.

In addition to my partner, I have a close group of friends who provided emotional support and encouragement. They would check in on me regularly and were always ready to listen if I needed to talk about my worries or experiences. Some of them are mothers themselves, so they could share their own stories and advice, which was comforting.

I also leaned on my family, particularly my mother, who has always been an advocate for my health. She was there to help with practical things like meal prep and even accompanied me to some of my appointments when I needed an extra set of ears to absorb the information.

Finally, my healthcare provider played a critical role in my support network. They not only provided medical care but also offered emotional reassurance and guidance throughout my pregnancies. I felt that I could always reach out to them with questions or concerns, which was incredibly valuable.

Overall, having a strong support system made a significant difference in my pregnancy experiences. I felt less alone in managing my health conditions and could focus more on enjoying the journey of becoming a parent.

Is there anything specific about my support network you'd like to know, or how it influenced my pregnancy experience?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Absolutely, I did put a lot of thought into my birth plan for both pregnancies, especially since I had already experienced cesarean deliveries. Given my medical history and the complications I faced, I wanted to ensure that my preferences were clearly communicated to my healthcare team.

For my first pregnancy, I was initially hopeful about having a vaginal delivery, but due to the complications that arose during labor, we ultimately decided on a cesarean section. Even though it wasn't the birth experience I had envisioned, I focused on the health of my baby and myself, which was the most important thing. 

With my second pregnancy, I was more informed and prepared. I discussed my options with my healthcare provider well in advance. While I was still open to the possibility of a vaginal delivery, we agreed that a repeat cesarean would likely be the safest option based on my previous experiences and health conditions. I appreciated that my obstetrician took the time to explain the reasons behind this recommendation, which helped me feel more at ease with the decision.

In both cases, I prioritized a calm and supportive environment during delivery. I wanted my partner to be there with me for emotional support, and we discussed the importance of creating a peaceful atmosphere in the operating room. I also expressed my desire for skin-to-skin contact with my baby immediately after delivery, which I was fortunate to experience both times.

Overall, while my birth experiences didn't follow the traditional path I initially envisioned, I felt empowered by the choices I made and the support I received from my healthcare team. It reinforced the importance of being flexible and prioritizing safety above all else.

Is there anything specific you would like to know about my birth plan or how I navigated the decisions around delivery?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I utilized a variety of sources to gather information about pregnancy and childbirth. First and foremost, I relied heavily on my healthcare provider. They provided valuable insights and guidance tailored to my specific health conditions and needs, which was incredibly helpful.

In addition to my healthcare provider, I read several reputable books on pregnancy and childbirth. One of my favorites was "What to Expect When You're Expecting," as it offered a comprehensive overview of the different stages of pregnancy and what to anticipate. I also explored books that focused on managing pre-existing conditions during pregnancy, which were particularly relevant to my situation.

Online resources were another significant source of information. I visited websites like the American Pregnancy Association and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) for reliable health information. I also found forums and online communities for expectant mothers to be a great way to connect with others going through similar experiences. Hearing their stories and tips helped me feel less alone.

Lastly, I attended prenatal classes offered by my clinic, where I learned about labor, delivery, and newborn care. These classes allowed me to ask questions and interact with other expectant parents, which made the experience even more enriching.

Overall, I felt it was essential to gather information from multiple sources to better prepare myself for the journey of pregnancy and childbirth. I wanted to be as informed as possible, especially given my unique health concerns.

Is there anything more specific you would like to know about the information sources I used or how they influenced my pregnancy experience?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby has been a significant consideration for me. Since I have private health insurance, I initially felt a bit more at ease knowing that many of my prenatal care costs would be covered. However, I still made it a priority to understand my insurance plan's coverage details, including co-pays for appointments, lab tests, and any potential costs associated with delivery.

I created a budget to help me plan for the various expenses associated with pregnancy and having a newborn. This included costs for prenatal vitamins, maternity clothes, baby gear, and nursery supplies. I also accounted for potential out-of-pocket costs related to cesarean deliveries, which can be higher than vaginal births. 

To prepare for maternity leave, I worked with my partner to ensure we had a financial plan in place. We discussed how long I would take off work and how that would impact our income. I utilized my small business resources to ensure I could maintain some level of income while I was on leave, and I saved up as much as possible in advance to cushion the financial impact during that period.

Additionally, I found it helpful to look into community resources and programs for new parents. There are local organizations that provide support, including baby supplies and parenting classes, which can help alleviate some of the financial burden.

Overall, while I was excited about the upcoming arrival of my baby, I knew that managing our finances carefully was essential to ensure a smooth transition into parenthood without added stress. 

Is there anything specific you’d like to know about my financial planning or how I navigated those aspects during my pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I found that my work and employment situation was impacted in several ways. As a small business owner, I had to carefully consider how to balance my responsibilities while preparing for the arrival of my children.

Initially, I was concerned about how my health conditions and the physical demands of pregnancy would affect my ability to run my business. I made adjustments to my schedule to accommodate my prenatal appointments and to ensure I was taking care of myself. I learned to delegate some tasks to trusted employees to lighten my workload, especially during the later stages of my pregnancies when I was more fatigued.

Additionally, I had to think about my maternity leave and how it would affect my business operations. I planned ahead by setting up systems to ensure that everything would run smoothly during my absence. This included training my staff on essential tasks and creating a clear plan for how to manage customer inquiries and orders while I was on leave.

Financially, I needed to prepare for the potential loss of income during my maternity leave. I saved ahead of time and created a budget to account for the time I would be away from work. I also explored options for short-term disability coverage, which could provide some financial support during that period.

The emotional aspect of transitioning into motherhood while managing a business was also significant. I often felt a mix of excitement about becoming a parent and anxiety about how it would impact my professional life. I sought support from other business owners who had gone through similar experiences, which helped me feel more prepared for the changes ahead.

Overall, while my pregnancies brought challenges to my work life, I tried to approach them with a proactive mindset. I focused on creating a balance that allowed me to prioritize both my health and my business, and I felt fortunate to have supportive staff and a partner who understood the demands of my situation.

Is there anything specific you’d like to know about how I managed my work during pregnancy or any particular challenges I faced?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Absolutely, I have given a lot of thought to the postpartum period and what it will entail after the baby arrives. I know that this time can be both rewarding and challenging, and having a plan in place is important to me.

One of my primary focuses is on my recovery after the cesarean delivery. I’ve been aware from my previous experiences that it’s crucial to allow myself time to heal physically. I plan to take a structured maternity leave to ensure I can focus on both my recovery and bonding with the baby. I’ve discussed this with my partner, and we’ve agreed that he will take some time off as well to support me during the initial weeks.

Emotionally, I know that the postpartum period can bring a range of feelings, from joy to anxiety. I intend to stay connected with my support network, including my partner, family, and friends, who can help me navigate any emotional challenges I might face. I’ve also considered joining a new parent support group, as I believe it could be beneficial to share experiences and gain insights from others going through similar transitions.

In terms of practical plans, I want to ensure that I have help with household tasks and childcare in the initial weeks. I’ve already talked to family members about their availability to assist us, whether it's cooking meals or helping with errands. I also plan to set up a support system of friends who can check in on me and provide companionship during those early days.

Additionally, I want to make sure that I keep up with my health management during the postpartum period. This means continuing to monitor my blood pressure and blood sugar levels and staying in touch with my healthcare provider for follow-up appointments. I’ve learned from my previous pregnancies that prioritizing my health is essential not only for me but also for my family.

Overall, I’m trying to approach the postpartum period with a mindset of flexibility and openness. I’m aware that things may not go exactly as planned, but I feel confident that with the right support and preparation, I will be able to navigate this new chapter successfully.

Is there anything specific you would like to know about my postpartum plans or how I’m preparing for that period?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
